definition (required): A synonym type for describing abbreviations or initalisms
example of use: CHEBI:26523 (reactive oxygen species) has an exact synonym (ROS), which is of type OMO:0003000 (abbreviation)

definition (required): A synonym type for describing ambiguous synonyms
A synonym type for describing dubious synonyms
A synonym type for describing layperson or colloquial synonyms
example of use: EFO:0006346 (severe cutaneous adverse reaction) has an exact synonym (scar), which is of the type OMO:0003003 (layperson synonym)

definition (required): A synonym type for describing pluralization synonyms
example of use: CHEBI:23367 (molecular entity) has an exact synonym (molecular entities), which is of the type OMO:0003004 (plural form)

definition (required): A synonym type for describing UK spelling variants
example of use: CHEBI:16189 (sulfate) has an exact synonym (sulphate), which is of the type OMO:0003005 (UK spelling synonym)

definition (required): A synonym type for common misspellings
A synonym type for misnomers, i.e., a synonym that is not technically correct but is commonly used anyway
A synonym type for names that have been used as primary labels in the past.
example of use: MAPT, the gene that encodes the Tau protein, has a previous name DDPAC. Note: in this case, the name type is more specifically the gene symbol.

definition (required): A synonym type for the legal entity name
example of use: The legal name for Harvard University (https://ror.org/03vek6s52) is President and Fellows of Harvard College

definition (required): The International Nonproprietary Name (INN) is a standardize name for a pharmaceutical drug or active ingredient issued by the World Health Organization (WHO) meant to address the issues with country- or language-specific brand names. These are issued in several languages, including English, Latin, French, Russian, Spanish, Arabic, and Chinese.
example of use: CHEBI:46195 has been assigned the english International Nonproproprietary Name (INN) "paracetamol". In some cases such as this one, the INN might be the same as the ontology's primary label

definition (required): A synonym type for describing Latin term synonyms.
example of use: nasopharynx (UBERON:0001728) has the latin name "pars nasalis pharyngis"

definition (required): A synonym type for describing abbreviations that are a part of the full name's words, such as initialisms or alphabetisms.
example of use: NASA is an word acronym for the US National Aeronautics and Space Administration because the acronym is pronounced. FBI is an initialism (also known as alphabetism) for the US Federal Bureau of Investigation since the letters are pronounced one at a time. JPEG is an acronym for Joint Photographic Experts Group but does not count as a word acronym nor an initialism since it is mixed how it is pronounced.

definition (required): An annotation property that links an ontology entity or a statement to a prefixed identifier or URI.
An information content entity that is a mark(s) or character(s) used as a conventional representation of another entity.
example of use: A serial number such as "12324X"; a stop sign; a written proper name such as "OBI"
